    "In 1865, Bismarck wanted Austria to sign a treaty that was entirely in Prussia's favor. The Austrian negotiator, Count Blome, fancied himself a judge of character through card games. The night before negotiations, Bismarck sat down with Blome and played quinze — recklessly, loudly, losing thousands of talers and making a fool of himself. Blome concluded that Bismarck was impulsive and incapable of deception. The next day, certain he had the advantage over a blundering fool, Blome barely glanced at the treaty before signing it. The moment the ink dried, Bismarck exclaimed that he could never have believed an Austrian diplomat would sign such a document. The performance had taken one evening. The diplomatic prize lasted a generation.",
